AGI - "I promise you that I will eventually be able to tell Pope Francis 'papele papele'". Lino Banfi jokes with journalists during the presentation in the Vatican of the event "The caress and the smile", the meeting that the Pontiff will have with grandparents, elders and grandchildren, next Saturday in the Paul VI Hall, promoted by the Foundation Age Great. Banfi told about his friendship with Francis, his peer ("we laugh so much together"), although, he emphasized the actor, "I have 6 months more than him and so I tell him 'Santity, he owes me respect... and he smiles." "Our friendship is getting stronger and stronger: there is mutual attraction, we have the same age and many affinities. We come from "blasoned" families, accounts that never came back. He calls me the grandfather of Italy, I call him 'the father of the mundo'&nbsp; (grandfather of the world), and so I exhorted to call him in choir at the meeting on Saturday.'
&nbsp;
Banfi also reported a recent meeting with the Pope, to whom he delivered a small poem that he then read to journalists: "It invites us to pray for the martyred Ukraine, and also for Israel and Palestine. And all, today, together with Pope Francis, grandfather of the world, giving us the hand, grandparents and grandchildren, we will do as a roundabout. It is not by this gesture that war will end, but something good will certainly come."
&nbsp;
<h2> Event </h2>
The event on Saturday, explained Mario Marazziti, of the Foundation Age Grande, will see, before the arrival of the Pontiff, a dialogue between Lino Banfi and Monsignor Vincenzo Paglia, president of the Pontifical Academy for Life, on the relationship between grandparents and grandchildren. On stage Al Bano and Eleonora Daniele will present everything. There will also be the choir of the diocese of Rome, directed by Monsignor Marco Frisina. When the Pope will be in the classroom, there are evidences, including that of a 91 year old, Sofia Soli who, becoming a widow, chose to live with other elderly.
&nbsp;
"It is an event that enrolls in a historical condition," said Monsignor Vincenzo Paglia. "For the first time they live in many countries - in Italy certainly - four generations together: it had never happened before. It is as if it had appeared, in the last decades, the fourth floor of a palace that describes generations. This building was filled by countless tenants and we didn't notice. We discovered it only, bitterly, during the Covid because the fourth floor, that of the elderly, was the most hawkish, we had already discarded it".
&nbsp;
In Italy, he added, "there are 14 million people on whom there is no political, economic, health, cultural and even religious thought. We're even afraid to use the word 'old'. The Saturday meeting "will not only be a beautiful event but can mean a step change within culture, society, economy and religion, on the basis of the indications that the Holy Father gave us, with his 19 catechesis on old age, on how to live Christianly those thirty years more than remain after retirement". Paglia finally remembered that with Law 33 the government "has radically reorganized the new assistance for the elderly. I hope it will be a contagious example for many other countries." &nbsp;

