AGI - A journey of more than 100 days and 12,000 kilometers to celebrate the 700th anniversary of Marco Polo's death. The expedition, inserted in the official calendar of the celebrations promoted by the National Committee established by the Ministry of Culture, will cross the lands narrated by "Il Milione" in an adventure between the references of the past and the challenges of the present. "We like to think that the motivations with which we embark on this venture are not so dissimilar to those that pushed Marco Polo to face his journey to Catai: the desire to know other worlds and other nations, and get in touch to foster dialogue and mutual understanding. Despite the times that are certainly different from those of Mark, we believe that today as then there is the same need for dialogue and listening among peoples, as recent tragic events at international level demonstrate," comments Fiorin and Facchinetti.
&nbsp;
The aim of the expedition is therefore to bring a message of peace and solidarity of which the bicycle, thanks to the slow and non-invasive approach with the territory it promotes, is a symbol. A "diplomacy of the bicycle", which will see Fiorin and Facchinetti engaged in institutional meetings in the various locations reached, thanks to the close collaboration with the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation and with the Embassies of the States crossed. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Marco Polo pedali is a journey that starts from afar, crossing the stories of Marco Polo and the city of Venice with the personal events of its protagonists. On April 25, 2001, Alberto Fiorin, a writer-trailer, left Venice with a group of nine cyclists to reach Beijing by bicycle. However, in Jesolo, at the 25th kilometer of the first stage, Fiorin had an accident that forced him to withdraw from the expedition. The desire to ride to Beijing never turned off: This is how, after many other cycling adventures and twenty-three years away, he felt that it was time to realize his old dream.
&nbsp;
The route, tested during the successful 2001 expedition, develops for about 12,000 kilometers in 100 days, through twelve nations: Italy, Slovenia, Croatia, Serbia, Bulgaria, Turkey, Georgia, Azerbaijan, Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan, Kazakhstan and China. The journey will consist of 85 stages for an average of 140 kilometers per day, and 15 days dedicated to visits and institutional meetings that will take place in Sofia (Bulgaria), Istanbul (Turkey), Samarcanda, (Uzbekistan), Almaty (Kazakistan) and Beijing (China). Fiorin and Facchinetti will travel with the Adlar 2024 model of Wilier Triestina (technical leader of the expedition), gravel bicycle, which will be loaded with four bags weighing about 18 kg.

